  {
    \"url\": \"https://x.com/CatAccept/status/2029137126055657812\",
    \"text\": \"🔥LLM judges aren't bad at reasoning — they're bad at knowing 𝘄𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝘁𝗼 𝗲𝘃𝗮𝗹𝘂𝗮𝘁𝗲. Same model, human rubrics → 𝟴𝟱% accuracy. Self-generated rubrics → 𝟱𝟴%. That's a 𝟮𝟳-𝗽𝗼𝗶𝗻𝘁 gap.\\nRubricBench (1,147 pairwise comparisons, 5 domains, expert-annotated atomic rubrics) finally puts a number on something we all suspected: the bottleneck in LLM-as-Judge isn't inference quality, it's rubric quality.\\n⚡THE PROBLEM\\nReward models keep getting fooled by surface signals. Longer response? Higher score. Better formatting? Higher score. Confident tone? Higher score. Whether the response actually solves the user's problem? Coin flip.\\nThe fix everyone's trying: rubric-guided evaluation. Extract checklist items from the instruction, verify each one. But those rubrics are also model-generated. Nobody had a benchmark to test whether models can even write good rubrics.\\n💡KEY FINDINGS\\n→ Traditional RMs and vanilla LLM judges score 𝟰𝟬-𝟱𝟬% on RubricBench (basically random)\\n→ Self-generated rubric methods reach 𝟱𝟱-𝟲𝟬%\\n→ Swap in human rubrics, same backbone → 𝟴𝟮-𝟴𝟱%\\nThe Rubric Gap is consistent across GPT-5.1, Gemini-3-Pro, Qwen3.5-Plus — no model escapes it.\\nScaling doesn't help either. Going from 4 to 32 auto-generated rubric items? Accuracy barely moves. But human rubrics from 2→8 items? Steady improvement. Models aren't generating too few criteria — they're generating the 𝘄𝗿𝗼𝗻𝗴 ones.\\n📊WHY MODELS FAIL AT RUBRIC GENERATION\\nStructural analysis: >𝟳𝟬% of model-generated rubric items are hallucinated (don't match any human criterion). Models love writing plausible-sounding checklist items that nobody actually cares about, while missing the constraints humans consider essential.\\nGreat case study: instruction says \\\"write Java to convert SQL→MongoDB, handle all cases.\\\" Human annotators flag that \\\"all cases\\\" is impossible — their rubric checks whether the response acknowledges infeasibility. Model rubric demands specific libraries and design patterns. Completely inverted judgments.\\n🧠MY TAKE\\nThe core insight is clean: models can't write good exam questions, even if they can grade when given the answer key. This reframes the next frontier — it's not about better reasoning during evaluation, it's about 𝗿𝘂𝗯𝗿𝗶𝗰 𝗮𝗹𝗶𝗴𝗻𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁.\\nEven with perfect rubrics, accuracy caps at ~85% due to execution failures (models secretly re-weight rubric items). Two independent capability gaps to close.\\nhttps://t.co/8EqHkjKTG3\\n💻\\nhttps://t.co/DPnoB5TdMF\\n#MachineLearning #AI #LLMEvaluation #RewardModeling\"
